Wrap the open/read/close sequence in a try/finally so the fd is always closed:
```ts
const fd = fs.openSync(realResolved, 'r');
let bytesRead: number;
try {
    bytesRead = fs.readSync(fd, buf, 0, MAX_FILE_READ_BYTES, 0);
} finally {
    fs.closeSync(fd);
}
```
Alternatively, replace the manual fd dance with `fs.readFileSync(realResolved, { encoding: 'utf8', flag: 'r' })` and slice to MAX_FILE_READ_BYTES bytes, which is self-closing.

Align hasToolCalls with the full-match requirement of parseToolCalls: check for a well-formed pair rather than just the opening tag:
```ts
export function hasToolCalls(text: string): boolean {
    return /<tool_call>[\s\S]*?<\/tool_call>/i.test(text);
}
```
This ensures the outer loop only re-prompts when there are actually parseable tool calls. Additionally, the calling loop should have an explicit max-iterations guard (e.g. 10) independent of per-batch MAX_CALLS.
